<subsection>
<title>Problems</title>
<p>
{ In Exercises}
{, prove the given limit using an <m>\epsilon - \delta</m> proof.}
</p>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 5} 3-x = -2</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-5|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-(-2)|\lt \epsilon</m>. 

Consider <m>|f(x)-(-2)|\lt \epsilon</m>:

<md><mrow>|f(x) + 2 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|(3-x) + 2 |\lt \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| 5-x | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  5-x \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  x-5 \lt  \epsilon.</mrow>
  
</md>
 
This implies we can let <m>\delta =\epsilon</m>. Then:

<md><mrow>|x-5|\lt \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>-\delta \lt  x-5 \lt  \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  x-5 \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  (x-3)-2 \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  (-x+3)-(-2) \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|3-x - (-2)| \lt  \epsilon,</mrow>
 
</md>
 
which is what we wanted to prove.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 3} x^2-3 = 6</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-3|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-6|\lt \epsilon</m>. 

Consider <m>|f(x)-6|\lt \epsilon</m>, keeping in  mind we want to make a statement about <m>|x-3|</m>:

<md><mrow>|f(x) -6 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^2-3 -6 |\lt \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x^2-9 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-3 |\cdot|x+3| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-3 | \lt  \epsilon/|x+3|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Since <m>x</m> is near 3, we can safely assume that, for instance, <m>2\lt x\lt 4</m>. Thus

<md><mrow>2+3\lt x+3\lt 4+3</mrow>
 <mrow>5 \lt  x+3 \lt  7</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{1}{7} \lt  \frac{1}{x+3} \lt  \frac{1}{5}</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{\epsilon}{7} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+3} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{5}</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Let <m>\delta =\frac{\epsilon}{7}</m>. Then:

<md><mrow>|x-3|\lt \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-3| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}7</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-3| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+3}</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-3|\cdot|x+3| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+3}\cdot|x+3|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Assuming <m>x</m> is near 3, <m>x+3</m> is positive and we can drop the absolute value signs on the right.

<md><mrow>|x-3|\cdot|x+3| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+3}\cdot(x+3)</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^2-9| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|(x^2-3) - 6| \lt  \epsilon,</mrow>
 
</md>
 
which is what we wanted to prove.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 4} x^2+x-5 = 15</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-4|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-15|\lt \epsilon</m>. 

Consider <m>|f(x)-15|\lt \epsilon</m>, keeping in  mind we want to make a statement about <m>|x-4|</m>:

<md><mrow>|f(x) -15 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^2+x-5 -15 |\lt \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x^2+x-20 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-4 |\cdot|x+5| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-4 | \lt  \epsilon/|x+5|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Since <m>x</m> is near 4, we can safely assume that, for instance, <m>3\lt x\lt 5</m>. Thus

<md><mrow>3+5\lt x+5\lt 5+5</mrow>
 <mrow>8 \lt  x+5 \lt  10</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{1}{10} \lt  \frac{1}{x+5} \lt  \frac{1}{8}</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{\epsilon}{10} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+5} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{8}</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Let <m>\delta =\frac{\epsilon}{10}</m>. Then:

<md><mrow>|x-4|\lt \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-4| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{10}</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-4| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+5}</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-4|\cdot|x+5| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+5}\cdot|x+5|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Assuming <m>x</m> is near 4, <m>x+5</m> is positive and we can drop the absolute value signs on the right.

<md><mrow>|x-4|\cdot|x+5| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x+5}\cdot(x+5)</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^2+x-20| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|(x^2+x-5) -15| \lt  \epsilon,</mrow>
 
</md>
 
which is what we wanted to prove.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} x^3-1 = 7</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-2|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-7|\lt \epsilon</m>. 

Consider <m>|f(x)-7|\lt \epsilon</m>, keeping in  mind we want to make a statement about <m>|x-2|</m>:

<md><mrow>|f(x) -7 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^3-1 -7 |\lt \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x^3-8 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-2 |\cdot|x^2+2x+4| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>| x-3 | \lt  \epsilon/|x^2+2x+4|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Since <m>x</m> is near 2, we can safely assume that, for instance, <m>1\lt x\lt 3</m>. Thus

<md><mrow>1^2+2\cdot1+4\lt x^2+2x+4\lt 3^2+2\cdot3+4</mrow>
 <mrow>7 \lt  x^2+2x+4 \lt  19</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{1}{19} \lt  \frac{1}{x^2+2x+4} \lt  \frac{1}{7}</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{\epsilon}{19} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x^2+2x+4} \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{7}</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Let <m>\delta =\frac{\epsilon}{19}</m>. Then:

<md><mrow>|x-2|\lt \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-2| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{19}</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-2| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x^2+2x+4}</mrow>
 <mrow>|x-2|\cdot|x^2+2x+4| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x^2+2x+4}\cdot|x^2+2x+4|</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Assuming <m>x</m> is near 2, <m>x^2+2x+4</m> is positive and we can drop the absolute value signs on the right.

<md><mrow>|x-2|\cdot|x^2+2x+4| \lt  \frac{\epsilon}{x^2+2x+4}\cdot(x^2+2x+4)</mrow>
 <mrow>|x^3-8| \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|(x^3-1) - 7| \lt  \epsilon,</mrow>
 
</md>
 
which is what we wanted to prove.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} 5 = 5</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-2|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-5|\lt \epsilon</m>. However, since <m>f(x)=5</m>, a constant function, the latter inequality is simply <m>|5-5|\lt \epsilon</m>, which is always true. Thus we can choose any <m>\delta</m> we like; we arbitrarily choose <m>\delta =\epsilon</m>.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} e^{2x}-1 = 0</m>
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-0|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-0|\lt \epsilon</m>. 

Consider <m>|f(x)-0|\lt \epsilon</m>, keeping in  mind we want to make a statement about <m>|x-0|</m> (i.e., <m>|x|</m>):

<md><mrow>|f(x) -0 | \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|e^{2x}-1 |\lt \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon\lt  e^{2x}-1 \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>1-\epsilon\lt  e^{2x} \lt  1+\epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>\ln (1-\epsilon) \lt  2x \lt  \ln (1+\epsilon)</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{\ln (1-\epsilon)}{2} \lt  x \lt  \frac{\ln (1+\epsilon)}{2}</mrow>
  
</md>
 
Let <m>\delta = \min\left\{\left|\frac{\ln(1-\epsilon)}{2}\right|,\frac{\ln(1+\epsilon)}{2}\right\}=\frac{\ln(1+\epsilon)}{2}.</m>

Thus:

<md><mrow>|x| \lt  \delta</mrow>
 <mrow>|x| \lt \frac{\ln(1+\epsilon)}{2}\lt \left|\frac{\ln(1-\epsilon)}{2}\right|</mrow>
 <mrow>\frac{\ln(1-\epsilon)}{2} \lt  x \lt  \frac{\ln(1+\epsilon)}{2}</mrow>
 <mrow>\ln(1-\epsilon)\lt  2x \lt  \ln(1+\epsilon)</mrow>
 <mrow>1-\epsilon \lt  e^{2x} \lt  1+\epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>-\epsilon \lt  e^{2x}-1 \lt  \epsilon</mrow>
 <mrow>|e^{2x}-1-(0)| \lt  \epsilon,</mrow>
 
</md>
 
which is what we wanted to prove.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
  
<exercise><statement>
<p>
<m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} \sin x= 0</m> (Hint: use the fact that <m>|\sin x| \leq |x|</m>, with equality only when <m>x=0</m>.)
</p>
  <hint>Let <m>\epsilon >0</m> be given. We wish to find <m>\delta >0</m> such that when <m>|x-0|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|f(x)-0|\lt \epsilon</m>. In simpler terms, we want to show that when <m>|x|\lt \delta</m>, <m>|\sin x| \lt  \epsilon</m>. 

Set <m>\delta = \epsilon</m>. We start with assuming that <m>|x|\lt \delta</m>. Using the hint, we have that <m>|\sin x | \lt  |x| \lt  \delta = \epsilon</m>. Hence if <m>|x|\lt \delta</m>, we know immediately that <m>|\sin x| \lt  \epsilon</m>.</hint> </statement>
</exercise>
